<!-- LA CONTEXT -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="context-grid">
      <div class="context-text">
        <p class="sl">Los Angeles Commercial Kitchen Context</p>
        <h2>LA restaurant kitchens run differently</h2>
        <p>Korean BBQ in Koreatown running ventless tabletop grills alongside hood-vented ranges. Sushi restaurants in West Hollywood with Hoshizaki ice machines on 24/7 ice production. Ghost kitchens in the Arts District running five brands out of one kitchen space with shared walk-in access. Fine dining on the Westside with Rational combi ovens and Hobart dishwashers that cost more than most residential appliances combined.</p>
        <p>LA's restaurant density is extreme. Koreatown alone has more restaurants per square mile than almost any neighborhood in the US. The equipment gets pushed hard, the hours are long, and when something fails it usually fails at the worst possible time — before service, during a rush, or on a weekend when other services won't respond.</p>
        <p>We've built our commercial service around LA's kitchen reality. Same day availability. Parts stocked for what LA restaurants actually run. A technician who can look a chef in the eye and explain what failed and why.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="facts">
        <div class="fact">
          <h4>🌡️ 41°F — The LADPH threshold</h4>
          <p>Walk-in failures above 41°F are a health code event in LA County. We treat these as priority dispatches because you should too.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="fact">
          <h4>👻 Ghost kitchen density in LA</h4>
          <p>LA has one of the highest ghost kitchen concentrations in the US — Arts District, Culver City, Koreatown. Equipment runs 16–18 hours/day. Failures are expensive fast.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="fact">
          <h4>💧 Hard water — ice & dishwasher impact</h4>
          <p>LA water runs 300–400 mg/L TDS. Ice machine scale and dishwasher heating element buildup happen faster than manufacturer maintenance schedules assume.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="fact">
          <h4>🌮 The food culture equation</h4>
          <p>From Korean BBQ to sushi to farm-to-table — LA's restaurant diversity means we see equipment configurations that most service companies don't encounter.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- HOW WE WORK -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">How It Works</p>
    <h2>What to expect when you call</h2>
    <p class="lead">No call center. No voicemail chess. A person who knows commercial equipment picks up and helps you triage the problem.</p>
    <div class="how-grid">
      <div class="how-step">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <h3>Call or request online</h3>
        <p>Tell us what's down, what brand, and what the symptoms are. We triage on the call — walk-in failures and food safety issues get same-day priority.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="how-step">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <h3>Technician on site</h3>
        <p>We give you a straight window. Tech arrives with parts for common failures. Full diagnosis before any repair work starts — you approve the quote first.</p>
      </div>
